text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Title: Consonant Inventories: Comparing English and %0a:Author: TimG%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 16.02.2021 - 19:46%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210314-190113-924160#%0a* [-14.03.2021 - 12:01-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210314-190113-924160#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aComparing the small consonant inventory of Hawaiian with the average inventory of English.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe consonant inventory of a language is the set of consonant sounds which speakers of the language use to create contrast, that is, the set of contrasting consonant sounds. The speakers of the language may produce other sounds when speaking (called allophones), but those sounds do not produce a difference in meaning. As one might expect, the feature values for consonant inventories range from small to large, with average in the middle. Thus, these values are relative to other languages.%0a%0aHawaiian famously has a very small consonant inventory (PHOIBLE say 9 distinct consonant sounds). This causes many different realizations of those consonant sounds, most notably the allophone for [k], [t]. English has a consonant inventory of average size, with somewhere between 24 and 27 phonemes depending on the dialect. %0a%0aIntuitively, this relatively tiny consonant inventory must make it very difficult for native Hawaiian speakers to learn other languages. Not being taught to differentiate consonants that (presumably) the other language you are trying to learn does differentiate would make every step of learning that language difficult. Has anyone researched this, and does my intuition hold up empirically?%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
